    {
      "id": "general_qwen_moe",
      "category": "general",
      "prompt": "Briefly explain what an MoE (mixture-of-experts) model is and one reason it's appealing vs a dense model of similar quality.",
      "gold_substrings": [
        "expert"
      ],
      "response": {
        "text": "An Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) model is a type of artificial intelligence architecture that combines multiple specialized models, or \"experts,\" to make decisions or predictions. Each expert is trained to handle a specific subset of tasks or data, and a gating mechanism determines which experts are activated for a given input. This approach allows the model to be more efficient and accurate, as it can leverage the strengths of each expert for specific tasks.\n\nOne reason an MoE model is appealing compared to a dense model of similar quality is its efficiency. MoE models can be more computationally efficient because they activate only a subset of experts for a given input, whereas dense models typically activate all their parameters. This can lead to faster inference times and lower computational costs, making MoE models more suitable for deployment in resource-constrained environments.",
